result.execSummary:
The defendant Victor M Delvalle-Cordero was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Armed Robbery [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: - Restitution is set at $1,150.00, payable to Wilson P.

- Defendant to pay court costs and all applicable surcharges, assessments and restitution to be collected by DOC from up to 25% of prison funds, balance to be paid during term of extended supervision; nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment.
- Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the DNA surcharge.
- Pay all supervision fees.
Concurrent with: concurrent to sentences in case #13CM1089 and #15CM1026, with credit for 461 DAYS time served.

superMiscConds.notes:
- Obtain/maintain full-time employment.
- Obtain GED or HSED.

- No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause.
- No contact with Wilson P., Marquis Walls and Duke.
- No alcohol or illegal drugs.

- Cooperate with any correctional programs recommended.
- Follow all rules of probation and extended supervision.

- AODA assessment and any recommended treatment.
- Absolute sobriety with random urine screens and breathalyzers.

supervisions.notes: Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions: firearm and body armor possession and voting.

Defendant Victor M Delvalle-Cordero in court with attorney Christian Thomas Eichenlaub.  Defendant Victor M Delvalle-Cordero in custody.  Patrick J Anderson for Ronald Dague appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: KAR.
Case calendared for sentencing hearing.  Spanish interpreter waived for this appearance.  State advised the Court they have complied with the Victims' Rights Law.  Offer placed on the record by the state.

AS TO COUNT 1: The Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 8 YEARS.  INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 3 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 5 YEARS, concurrent to sentences in case #13CM1089 and #15CM1026, with credit for 461 DAYS time served.  Defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and is not eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
- Restitution is set at $1,150.00, payable to Wilson P.
- Defendant to pay court costs and all applicable surcharges, assessments and restitution to be collected by DOC from up to 25% of prison funds, balance to be paid during term of extended supervision; nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment.
- Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the DNA surcharge.
- No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause.
- Cooperate with any correctional programs recommended.
- Follow all rules of probation and extended supervision.
- Pay all supervision fees.
- Obtain/maintain full-time employment.
- Obtain GED or HSED.
- No contact with Wilson P., Marquis Walls and Duke.
- AODA assessment and any recommended treatment.
- Absolute sobriety with random urine screens and breathalyzers.
- No alcohol or illegal drugs.

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions: firearm and body armor possession and voting.  Defendant advised of appeal rights.

Defendant Victor M Delvalle-Cordero in court with attorney Christian Thomas Eichenlaub.  Defendant Victor M Delvalle-Cordero in custody.  Ronald Dague appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sworn as interpreter:  Enrique Barbosa.  Defendant changes plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon he may no longer use or possess any firearms; also he may not vote in any election until his civil rights have been restored.  Court further advised that if he is not a US citizen, deportation is possible.  Court ordered defendant provide a DNA sample and pay applicable surcharges.  Payment of these surcharges will be addressed on the day of sentencing.  
Defendant has a pending matter that is scheduled for Jury Trial on March 28, 2016.  Sentencing will be conducted on this matter upon resolution of the pending jury trial case.  Status conference scheduled for March 28, 2016 at 10:00 am.
